To create a GTK window in C# and load the provided XML interface, you'll need to use the GtkSharp library. 
Make sure to install the required NuGet packages for GtkSharp (Gtk3 and Gdk3), then you can use the following code:

```csharp
using System;
using Gtk;
using UI = Gtk.Builder.ObjectAttribute;

public class TodoListApp : Application
{
    [UI] private ApplicationWindow mainWindow = null;

    public TodoListApp() : base("org.example.TodoListApp", ApplicationFlags.None) { }

    protected override void OnActivate()
    {
        base.OnActivate();
        var builder = new Builder();
        builder.AddFromString(xmlInterface);
        builder.Autoconnect(this);
        mainWindow.ShowAll();
    }

    private static string xmlInterface = @"<!-- The XML string containing your UI design -->";

    public static void Main(string[] args)
    {
        Application.Init();
        var app = new TodoListApp();
        app.Run(args);
    }
}
```

Replace <!-- The XML string containing your UI design --> with the XML string containing the UI design you provided earlier.
This code defines a TodoListApp class that inherits from the Gtk.Application class. The OnActivate method is overridden to load the provided XML interface using the Gtk.Builder class. The Autoconnect method is used to connect the C# class members with the corresponding widgets in the XML.
Remember to install the GtkSharp NuGet packages before running the code.

Sure thing! But note, that this C# is just the interface, and it also requires you to install **GTK** to your machine. Here is the code that loads this interface:

```cs
using Gtk;

public class MainWindow : Gtk.Window
{
    public MainWindow() : base("To-Do List")
    {
        // Set default size of window
        SetDefaultSize(600, 400);

        // Create a box to hold the grid and the task list
        Box box = new Box(Orientation.Vertical, 10);

        // Create a grid to hold the task entry and due date entry
        Grid grid = new Grid();
        grid.ColumnHomogeneous = true;
        grid.RowSpacing = 6;
        grid.ColumnSpacing = 6;
        grid.MarginStart = 10;
        grid.MarginEnd = 10;
        grid.MarginTop = 10;
        grid.MarginBottom = 10;

        // Add task label and entry to grid
        Label taskLabel = new Label("Task:");
        grid.Attach(taskLabel, 0, 0, 1, 1);
        Entry taskEntry = new Entry();
        taskEntry.Name = "task_entry";
        grid.Attach(taskEntry, 1, 0, 1, 1);

        // Add due date label and entry to grid
        Label dueDateLabel = new Label("Due Date:");
        grid.Attach(dueDateLabel, 0, 1, 1, 1);
        Entry dueDateEntry = new Entry();
        dueDateEntry.Name = "due_date_entry";
        grid.Attach(dueDateEntry, 1, 1, 1, 1);

        // Add "Add Task" button to grid
        Button addButton = new Button("Add Task");
        addButton.Expand = false;
        addButton.Halign = Align.End;
        addButton.Valign = Align.End;
        addButton.Clicked += OnAddTaskButtonClicked;
        grid.Attach(addButton, 1, 2, 1, 1);

        // Add grid to box
        box.Add(grid);

        // Create a scrolled window to hold the task list
        ScrolledWindow scrolledWindow = new ScrolledWindow();
        scrolledWindow.HscrollbarPolicy = PolicyType.Never;
        scrolledWindow.VscrollbarPolicy = PolicyType.Always;

        // Create a list box to hold the tasks
        ListBox listBox = new ListBox();
        listBox.Name = "task_list";

        // Add list box to scrolled window
        scrolledWindow.Add(listBox);

        // Add scrolled window to box
        box.Add(scrolledWindow);

        // Add box to window
        Add(box);

        // Show all widgets
        ShowAll();
    }

    private void OnAddTaskButtonClicked(object sender, EventArgs args)
    {
        // TODO: Implement task adding functionality
    }

    public static void Main(string[] args)
    {
        Application.Init();

        MainWindow mainWindow = new MainWindow();
        mainWindow.DeleteEvent += delegate { Application.Quit(); };
        mainWindow.Show();

        Application.Run();
    }
}
```

Some things to note: I commented the code, so you can understand how something works. I added a "TODO", so you will have to implement the functionality of adding tasks. Also, note that this is just a **beginning point**, and is **not** production-ready.

Certainly! Here are simple examples in three different languages, one from each category: interpreted (Python), compiled (C), and JIT-compiled (Java).

1. Interpreted Language Example (Python):
```python
def greeting(name):
    return f"Hello, {name}!"

name = input("Please enter your name: ")
print(greeting(name))
```

2. Compiled Language Example (C):
```c
#include <stdio.h>

void greeting(char name[]) {
    printf("Hello, %s!\n", name);
}

int main() {
    char name[50];
    printf("Please enter your name: ");
    fgets(name, sizeof(name), stdin);
    greeting(name);
    return 0;
}
```

3. JIT-Compiled Language Example (Java):
```java
import java.util.Scanner;

public class Greeting {

    public static String greeting(String name) {
        return "Hello, " + name + "!";
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Scanner scanner = new Scanner(System.in);
        System.out.print("Please enter your name: ");
        String name = scanner.nextLine();
        System.out.println(greeting(name));
    }
}
```

All three examples have the same functionality: they prompt the user to enter their name, and then display a personalized greeting. However, each example is written in a different programming language, illustrating the different styles of interpreted, compiled, and JIT-compiled languages.

